---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';
---
<Base title="Who Is This For" section={4}>
  <SectionHeader n={4} title="Who Is This For" meta="~400w" />

  <div class="prose">

    <p>
      The most common dashboard failure is not a bad metric or a misleading chart.
      It is a dashboard specced by someone with authority and used by someone with context
      who are rarely the same person. Call this the audience mismatch problem, and
      understand that it is endemic — not exceptional.
    </p>

    <p>
      The VP of Marketing commissions a campaign performance dashboard. She wants
      high-level health metrics: reach, conversion, cost per acquisition, trend lines.
      She will glance at it in the fifteen minutes before a review meeting. What she
      gets is a dashboard used almost exclusively by the two analysts on her team,
      who needed something different entirely — breakdowns by channel, by creative,
      by cohort, exportable to CSV so they can run their own models on top of it.
      The dashboard serves neither of them well. It is too operational for the VP
      and too shallow for the analysts. Nobody asked who the actual user was.
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      <p>The dashboard designed for the CEO that only the analyst reads.
      Audience mismatch is endemic — dashboards get specced by someone with authority
      and used by someone with context. They're rarely the same person.</p>
    </PullQuote>

    <p>
      The question "who is this for?" sounds obvious. It is not asked. The reason it
      is not asked is that dashboards get commissioned top-down and built bottom-up,
      and the people in the middle — the ones doing the building — assume the commissioning
      person is the user. Sometimes they are. More often, the executive who asked for
      the dashboard will look at it twice, send a screenshot to someone, and then forget
      it exists. The person who uses it daily is three levels down, doing something
      the executive never imagined.
    </p>

    <p>
      There is no single fix, but there is a useful discipline: before opening any
      chart tool, write the name of the person who will look at this data most often.
      Not the person who asked for it — the person who will actually use it.
      Then write down the question they are trying to answer when they open it.
      If you cannot do this, you are not ready to build yet. Go talk to that person.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="Corollary">
      If the dashboard genuinely serves multiple audiences — and sometimes it does —
      it should be multiple dashboards. A shared screen with opposing information needs
      is not a compromise. It is a failure that satisfies nobody.
    </Annotation>

    <p>
      The deeper issue is that dashboard design inherits the power structure of the
      organisations that commission it. Data gets surfaced upward, toward the people
      who control budget and headcount. The people closest to the work — the ones who
      most need good data tooling to do their jobs — often get the least considered
      interfaces. This is not malice. It is just how organisational gravity works.
      The person who makes the request has the most pull.
    </p>

    <p>
      Good dashboard design reverses this, at least partially. It starts with the person
      doing the work, builds for their actual question, and then asks what subset of
      that information needs to be surfaced to higher levels — and in what simplified
      form. The executive view is a derived product of the operational view, not the
      other way around.
    </p>

  </div>
</Base>
